[***2(b). Acceptable Use.***]{style="color:royalblue;"}

One current ethical discussion in data science involves the training of "Large Language Models" such as ChatGPT. These models are trained using massive corpora (document sets) that include large amounts of work that is covered under copyright law. Read the following two articles:

-   [Do Large Language Models Violate Copyright Law?](https://www.dykema.com/news-insights/do-large-language-models-violate-copyright-law.html)
-   [Reexamining "Fair Use" in the Age of AI](https://hai.stanford.edu/news/reexamining-fair-use-age-ai)

Write a short paragraph (maximum 8 sentences) discussing the arguments on both sides of the discussion over copyright in training large language models.

The use of copyrighted materials for the purposes of training generative AI models is a complicated and nuanced issue that falls squarely within a legal and even moral gray area. On the side of the creator and copywriter, the use of their material for the purpose of making money would appear to fall directly within existing legal precedent that this would not be appropriate. Furthermore, the products churned out by Gen AI models are often quite similar to the original work of the creator. It is also contended that the largest source of information used for these models are illegal and non compliant with US Copyright laws. On the other hand, Gen AI backers argue that the libraries that they allegedly sourced this data from is the problem, not Gen AI or the developers themselves. Additionally, the creators argue that it would still be fine if they had purchased the materials directly from the original creators and used that to train their models. Many supporters of Gen AI also argue that humans are taught and trained in the exact same way that Gen AI was, as a derivation from previous works, but that such educational purposes don't constitute copyright violation.
